AVL/RB-trees in C# OOP style.

Description:
This project provides a scalable, ground-up implementation of self-balancing search trees in C#.
It features AVL and Left-Leaning-Red-Black trees that guarantee O(logn) time complexity of insertions/deletions/lookups.

Additionally, the proejct includes standard higher-level library collections (Dictionary and Set) that utilize balanced trees, 
however can be easily reinitialzied to use any other data-structure thanks to the generic design.

Goal:
The goal of the project was to put theory into practice and to explore C# OOP structures.

Implementations:
    BST-Tree: a generic abstract base class that handles basic binary trees operations;

    AVL-Tree: a standard balanced AVL Tree that maintains height invariant via single/double rotations. Height updates are propagated to the root of the tree, which allows to cut several corner-cases, although sacrifacing a bit of perfomance compared to the signal implementation;

    LLRB-Tree: a standard textbook variant of a more general Red-Black tree, which, however, maintains all its complexity analysis;

    Generic-Dictionary: a key-value map, can be injected with arbitary data-structure that satisfies IKeyValuePair interface;

    Generic-Set: a collection of unique elements, can be injected with arbitary data-structure that satisfies IKeyValuePair interface;

Major issues:
Multiple node casts e.g: Node into RBNode, Node into AVLNode and vice-versa stands-out from OOP design paradigm and potentially also halts efficiency.

Usage:
Tests class provides basic usage examples.
